3 NEW SECTION. Section 6. Damages. (1) Damages, except as provided in subsection (3), awarded
4 under this section are:
5 (a) $65,000 $80,000 for each year of imprisonment; and
6 (b) $25,000 for each additional year served on parole or probation supervision or for each
7 additional year the claimant was required to register as a sexual or violent offender, whichever is greater.
8 (2) Compensation awarded under [sections 1 through 8] is not subject to the monetary limitation
9 under 2-9-108.
10 (3) All damages must be paid out of the account provided for in [section 8].
11 (4) A claimant is not entitled to receive compensation for any period of imprisonment during which
12 the claimant was concurrently serving a sentence for a conviction of another crime for which the claimant was
13 lawfully convicted and incarcerated.
14 (5) (a) Except as provided in subsection (5)(b), the court shall order that the award be paid as a
15 combination of an initial payment not to exceed $100,000 or 25% of the award, whichever is greater, and the
16 remainder as an annuity not to exceed $80,000 a year.
17 (b) (i) On July 1 of each year, the award increases by an amount equal to the percentage increase,
18 if any, for the preceding calendar year in the annual average consumer price index for urban wage earners,
19 compiled by the bureau of labor statistics of the United States department of labor or its successor agency.
20 (ii) The amount for any partial year must be prorated in order to compensate only for the portion of
21 the year when the claimant was incarcerated.
22 (c) The claimant shall designate a beneficiary or beneficiaries for the annuity by filing a beneficiary
23 designation with the court.
24 (d) The court may order that the award be paid in one lump sum if the court finds that it is in the
25 best interests of the claimant.
26 (6) (a) In addition to the damages awarded pursuant to subsection (1), a claimant:
